A '''''film à clef''''' (or '''''cinéma à clef''''', '''''movie à clef''''',<ref name="id.l_Film"/> '''''film à clé''''' ({{IPA-fr|film‿a kle}}, French for "film with a key"), is a [[film]] describing real life, behind a façade of [[fiction]].<ref name="Truffaut1994">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VxFomoeKT74C&pg=PA131#v=onepage |title=The films in my life|first=François|last= Truffaut|isbn=978-0-306-80599-8| page =131 |publisher=Da Capo Press |date=1994 |accessdate=2012-05-01}}</ref> "Key" in this context means a table one can use to swap out the names.
''Film à clef'' is the film equivalent of the literary ''[[roman à clef]]'', and the two share the same techniques.<ref name="id.l_Film"/>
Many ''films à clef'' are [[biopic]]s of Hollywood personalities.<ref name="id.l_Film"/>
==Notable ''films à clef''== {{refimprove section|date=August 2017}} *''[[8½]]'' (1963) is based on [[Federico Fellini]]'s experience suffering from "[[Writer's block|director's block]]." *''[[21 (2008 film)]]''(2008) *''[[Adaptation (film)|Adaptation]]'' (2002); while parts of the film are adapted from [[Susan Orlean]]'s non-fiction book ''[[The Orchid Thief]]'', most of the film is a heavily fictionalized account of [[Charlie Kaufman]]'s difficulty in adapting the book into a screenplay. *''[[All About Eve]]'' (1950) *''[[All Good Things (film)|All Good Things]]'' (2010) is inspired by the life of [[Robert Durst]]. *''[[All the King's Men (1949 film)|All the King's Men]]'' (1949), is based on the life of [[Huey Long]]. *''[[All That Jazz (film)]]'' (1979) musical film by Bob Fosse loosley based on his struggle with life and health during post production of his film [[Lenny (film)]] and his Broadway musical [[Chicago (musical)]]. *''[[Almost Famous]]'' (2000), is based on writer, director [[Cameron Crowe]]'s experience as a teenaged writer for Rolling Stone magazine. *''[[Alpha Dog]]'' (2006), based on the story of [[Jesse James Hollywood]] and the [[murder of Nicholas Markowitz]]. *''[[Annie Hall]]'' (1977), believed to be a version of [[Woody Allen]]'s own relationship with [[Diane Keaton]] (whose birth name is Diane Hall). Allen has denied this in interviews, however. *''[[The Birth of a Nation]]'' (1915), Austin Stoneman is based on [[Thaddeus Stevens]]. *''[[The Carpetbaggers (film)|The Carpetbaggers]]'' (1964),<ref name="id.l_Film" /> based on the book by [[Harold Robbins]], whose main character, Jonas Cord, is influenced by [[Howard Hughes]] *''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]'' (1995) is based on [[Frank Rosenthal]] and the [[Stardust Resort and Casino|Stardust]] casino. *''[[Citizen Kane]]'' (1941), is partially based on the life of [[William Randolph Hearst]].<ref name="id.l_Film">{{Cite web | title = Films à clef - LC Linked Data Service: Authorities and Vocabularies | publisher = Library of Congress | work = id.loc.gov | accessdate = 16 August 2017 | url = http://id.loc.gov/authorities/genreForms/gf2016026012.html }}</ref> *''[[A Cock and Bull Story]]'' (2015) <ref name="Smith2010">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Damon|title=Michael Winterbottom: Interviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m6ajgj74QicC&pg=PA98|year=2010|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-841-4|page=98}}</ref> *''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]'' (2006) is based on ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine editor [[Anna Wintour]]. *''[[Diva (1981 film)|Diva]]'' (1981) is based on the early European career of soprano [[Jessye Norman]]. *''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]'' (2006), the [[musical film]] based on the career of [[The Supremes]]. *''[[Festen|The Celebration]]'' (1998) was based on an alleged real-life story that director [[Thomas Vinterberg]] heard on Danish radio. *''[[The Five Heartbeats]]'' (1991) inspired loosely by the lives of [[The Temptations|The]] [[The Temptations|Temptations]], [[The Dells|The]] [[The Dells|Dells]], [[Four Tops|The Four Tops]], [[Wilson Pickett]], [[James Brown]], [[Sam Cooke]], [[Frankie Lymon]] and others. *''[[The Goddess (1958 film)|The Goddess]]''<ref name="id.l_Film" /> (1958) said to be based on [[Marilyn Monroe]]. *''[[The Greek Tycoon]]'' (1978),<ref name="id.l_Film" /> influenced by [[Aristotle Onassis]]. *''[[The Great Dictator]]'' (1940), Adenoid Hynkel is based on [[Adolf Hitler]]. *''[[Guru (2007 film)|Guru]]'' (2007), based on the rise and business practices of [[Dhirubhai Ambani]]. *''[[I'm Not There]]'' (2007), a series of stories loosely inspired by the life of [[Bob Dylan]]. While some segments are more literal interpretations of parts of Dylan's life (such as the segment featuring [[Cate Blanchett]]), others are heavily fictionalized accounts inspired by Dylan's music (such as the segment featuring [[Richard Gere]]). *''[[Imitation of Life (1934 film)|Imitation of Life]]'' (1934) <ref name="id.l_Film" /> *''[[Last Days (film)|Last Days]]'' (2005), a barely concealed dramatization of [[Kurt Cobain]]'s final days. *''[[The Last Samurai]]'' (2003), inspired by the 1876 [[Satsuma Rebellion]] and also on the story of [[Jules Brunet]], a French army captain who fought in the [[Boshin War]]. *''[[The Last Tycoon (1976 film)|The Last Tycoon]]'' (1976) <ref name="id.l_Film" /> *''[[The Life Aquatic with Steve Zissou]]'' (2004), which features a protagonist based loosely on [[Jacques-Yves Cousteau]]. *''[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]]'' (2003); Charlotte and John are believed to be based loosely on writer-director [[Sofia Coppola]] and her ex-husband, [[Spike Jonze]]. *''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942) *''[[Magnolia (film)|Magnolia]]'' (1999), is loosely inspired by [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]'s experience in dealing with his father's death from cancer. *''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]'' (1976) <ref name="id.l_Film" /> *''[[The Power and the Glory (1933 film)|The Power and the Glory]]'' (1933) is loosely based on the life of [[C.W. Post]]. *''[[Primary Colors (film)|Primary Colors]]'' (1998) is a thinly veiled depiction of [[Bill Clinton]]'s [[Bill Clinton presidential campaign, 1992|1992 presidential campaign]]. * The killers in ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960), ''[[The Texas Chain Saw Massacre]]'' (1974), and ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'' (1991) are all modeled closely after [[Ed Gein]], who murdered two women, robbed many graves, and made clothing and furniture out of human skin and bones. *''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'' (1998), based loosely on the [[Niland brothers]]. *''[[Scarface (1932 film)|Scarface]]'' (1932) is largely based on the life of [[Al Capone]]. *''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]'' (1939), Doc Boone is based on [[Doc Holliday]]. *''[[A Star Is Born (1937 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' (1937){{sfn|Stam|Raengo|2008|p=235}} *''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]'' (1950)<ref name="id.l_Film" /> *''[[Sweet Smell of Success]]'' (1957), is based on the life of [[Walter Winchell]]. *''[[Velvet Goldmine]]'' (1998) is largely based on the career of [[David Bowie]]. *''[[White Hunter Black Heart]]'' (1990) <ref name="Vaux2014">{{cite book|author=Sara Anson Vaux|title=Clint Eastwood: A Biography: A Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SBeDBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|year=2014|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-2998-7|page=83}}</ref> based on film director [[John Huston]] *''[[Withnail & I]]'' (1987) is based on the experiences of writer/director [[Bruce Robinson]], represented in the film by "I" ([[Paul McGann]]), and his friend [[Vivian MacKerrell]], represented in the film by Withnail ([[Richard E. Grant]]), as struggling actors living in [[Camden Town]] in the late 1960s. The character of Uncle Monty ([[Richard Griffiths]]) is based on Italian film director [[Franco Zeffirelli]], who Robinson claims made amorous advances during the filming of ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]''.
